requirement description

Rpaper

Use R code to draw the gene function enrichment analysis bubble map from the paper, it looks good arranged diagonally

Heat maps are solved with code 9, this code solves bubble maps

usage scenario

Scenario 1: Present the results of gene function enrichment analysis

Scenario 2: Multi-dimensional data information display

Input data

easy_input.txt

TermPvaluenumber of genes in group(test, Pop.Hits)number of annotated gene(background, Count)Gene Ratio(test/background)

The left half of the example shows down-regulated genes, while the right side shows up-regulated genes.

We all use the easy_input.txt file here, just replace it with the results of your enrichment analysis when you actually apply it.

Include at least: Term, Pvalue, number of genes in group (test, Pop.Hits), number of annotated gene (background, Count) or Gene Ratio (test/background)

df <- read.table("easy_input.txt", header = T, sep = "\t", as.is = T)
head(df)
##                                                     Term Count Pop.Hits  PValue
## 1 regulation of transcription, DNA-templat... GO:0006355   206       73 0.00028
## 2                     metanephros development GO:0001656    17        8 0.00147
## 3                     hippocampus development GO:0021766     8        7 0.00515
## 4 negative regulation of transcription fro... GO:0000122    62       25 0.01306
## 5                         response to glucose GO:0009749    13        8 0.01922
## 6       G1/S transition of mitotic cell cycle GO:0000082     9        6 0.01959
# gene ratio
# calculate the gene ratio
df$GeneRatio <- df$Pop.Hits/df$Count

Start drawing

GeneRatiopvalue

The horizontal coordinate of the example plot represents GeneRatio, the size of the dots indicates the number of genes in the group, and the color represents the p-value.

In practical applications, you can modify the feature values represented by the horizontal coordinates, colors, or point sizes to the other columns you want.

# GeneRatiox
# viewing the maximum and minimum values of GeneRatio can be used to determine a reasonable range for the x-axis
summary(df$GeneRatio)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.3544  0.4725  0.6410  0.6613  0.8438  1.0000
# GeneRatio
# To draw a diagonal arrangement effect, sorted by GeneRatio
sortdf <- df[order(df$GeneRatio), ] #PvalueGeneRatioPValue If you want to sort by Pvalue, change the GeneRatio to PValue
sortdf$Term <- factor(sortdf$Term, levels = sortdf$Term)

pl <- ggplot(sortdf, aes(GeneRatio, Term, # horizontal and vertical coordinates
              colour = PValue)) + # p-value color represents p-values
  geom_point(aes(size= Count)) + # the size of the dots represents the number of genes in the group
  scale_size_continuous(range = c(2,10)) + # size range of the dot
  scale_color_gradientn(colours=c("red", "yellow")) + # you can change the color yourself
  #scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0.2,1)) + #x set the x-axis range
  theme_bw() + 
  ylab("") + 
  theme(legend.position=c(1,0), legend.justification = c(1, 0)) + #legend the legend is drawn in the lower right corner
  #legend
  #the next two lines make the legend fit into the plot
  theme(legend.background = element_blank()) + #legend remove the overall border of the legend
  theme(legend.key = element_blank())#legend remove the border around each item in the legend

decreasing = T

termscale_y_discrete(position = right)

To sort in the opposite direction, just add decreasing = T

Put term on the right, add scale_y_discrete(position = right)

sortdf <- df[order(df$GeneRatio, decreasing = T), ] # descending order
sortdf$Term <- factor(sortdf$Term, levels = sortdf$Term)

pr <- ggplot(sortdf, aes(GeneRatio, Term, 
              colour=PValue)) + 
  geom_point(aes(size=Count)) + 
  scale_color_gradientn(colours=c("red", "yellow")) + 
  scale_size_continuous(range = c(2, 10)) + 
  #scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0.2, 1)) + 
  ylab("") + 
  scale_y_discrete(position = "right") + #term put term on the right
  
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(legend.position=c(0, 0), legend.justification = c(0, 0)) + #legend the legend is drawn in the lower left corner
  theme(legend.background = element_blank()) + 
  theme(legend.key = element_blank())
pr
